This is the first guitar I ever bought.  I somehow got $770 together when I was 13… and I crushed the salespersons spirit into bits and pieces getting them to give it to me for that price… plus 6 sets of strings, and to include $160 case… and to set it up etc.  I was ruthless. I also wouldn’t buy any guitar until I could afford one that I knew I’d never have to upgrade from.  It’s so sentimental being able to play this strat in front of these crowds!(I’ve never toured a big tour with it til now). Also… jess makes me feel like I need to workout my arms more.
I feel like Jax could very easily topple me with just a little extra shove.  Also…. Who knew my hair would stay pink long enough to be giving Barbie vibes

Here’s how to use AutoTune JUST LIKE T-Pain🎵

Watching T-Pain in the studio when I worked on “Thug Story”, I saw how he tracks THROUGH autotune, so that it’s permanently printed as he heard it in his headphones while singing.  This also allows you to listen with the lowest latency because you’re only using one plugin of AutoTune no matter how many tracks you record. 

1. Create an aux track and add autotune. 
2. Route the output of that track to an audio track that will record your vocal(after it’s passed through the aux with autotune). 
3. Setup a few tracks that are routed to one lead vocal aux track and use a single vocal suite plug in on that track. (You can do an additional one for bgvs. 
4. Add verb and delay sends from the vocal aux’s. 

Now you’re able to control the vocals you’ve already sang, with one or two aux tracks‼️

Here’s how to save on CPU usage, so you can get your latency buffer speed all the way down without your computer glitching out.  Whether you’re singing through AutoTune like T-Pain, or recording instruments or midi… no one wants to perform while hearing a delayed playback. 

Once you’ve got your instrumental track produced and roughly mixed, route ALL of the outputs to an aux track. 

Group the selected tracks with “command + G” so you can change the volume and avoid clipping the aux track. 

Now add a mastering suite or limiter to the aux track(this will make sure nothing is too quiet or jumps too loudly while recording to it). 

“Commit” your aux/mix buss, so that it’s a stereo track with no plug ins being used. 

Make all the tracks of your instrumental “inactive” so they don’t take up any CPU(you’re overdubbing ONLY to the stereo instrumental now.  So easy to control the volume of the track for singers preferences too)

Make sure your “master” fader/track is “inactive”. Otherwise there will still be latency. 

#protools #audioengineer #musicproducer #musicproduction #vocalproducer #vocalproduction #autotune

Save your CPU PART 2!

If you want to record vocals through AutoTune like T-Pain, or track an instrument without any latency or lag… you’ll need to lower your CPU usage and decrease your buffer size, and here’s a great way to do it. 

Watch part 1 on how to group the instrumental that’s already produced, into a 2-track/stereo mix. 

Aside from your vocal track your recording into…
Create a lead vocal audio track. 

Route the output to a LEAD VOX aux track. 

On the lead aux, add a vocal suite plug in(like the one I used in the “pro vocals in seconds” video). 
Remove the compression from the vocal suite(because you may have a couple vocals come through at once, and it would squash them weirdly). You can compress on the vocal audio track itself if needed. Or record through a compressor(outboard or printed on an aux in track). 

Add reverb and delay sends from the lead vocal aux. 

Duplicate the lead vocal AUDIO track for as many parts(verses, choruses etc) as you need. Even a left and right pair of doubles can be fed into this buss. 

for BGVs,
Create 4 audio tracks. Pan 2 left, and 2 right. Group them with “command G”. 
Send their outputs to an aux/buss.  Now you can control their volume with that aux. 
repeat this depending on how many BGV parts you need. 

Route the outputs from all the BGV auxs to a single “BGV buss” aux track. Use the same vocal suite plug in you used on the LEAD VOX aux.  add the same reverb and delay sends. 

Now you’re able to have a ton of vocals going, while only using 2 vocal suite plug ins… a reverb.  A delay.  And whatever autotune or instrument you’re currently recording.
